<DOC><DOCNO> AP890623-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0656EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-23 0561</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0578</SECOND><HEAD>Rain Soaks Much of Nation</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Rain fell in much of the nation today and caused flooding inwestern New York after flash floods in Pennsylvania led to thedrowning death of a disabled woman.   Early morning showers and thunderstorms extended today fromOklahoma across Wisconsin into western Indiana, and across northernparts of the Virginias and from Georgia across Florida.   A state of emergency was declared for Genesee County in westernNew York, where heavy rains washed out parts of some roads and leftsome elevated railroad bridges in danger of collapsing. Roads alsowere washed out or closed by flooding in three other counties. AtArcade, 3{ inches of rain fell Thursday evening.   Flood watches were posted through the morning in much of thecentral and southern Appalachians and a large part of western NewYork.   Heavy thunderstorms in southeastern Pennsylvania unleashed flashfloods that stranded rush-hour commuters Thursday and led to a freakdrowning accident, authorities said.   Linda J. Sanford, a 22-year-old woman with cerebral palsy, wassitting in her family room at her home in Holland when the roomfilled with about 2{ feet of water, said Detective Ken Barnes of theNorthampton Township Police Department. She apparently fell into thewater and drowned, Barnes said.   Rain soaked parts of Alabama again Thursday, with thunderstormsdowning trees and power lines in Chilton, Cullman and Talladegacounties. Birmingham's suburb of Leeds received nearly 1.7 inches ofrain.   Rain that flooded farmers' crops and inundated homes has causedat least $2 million in damage in east-central Alabama, officialssaid Thursday.   More harsh weather also hit Georgia Thursday afternoon, withlightning sparking at least three house fires in Gwinnett County,one of which injured four firefighters when a roof collapsed on them.   A Fire Department spokesman said the firefighters were taken toGwinnett Medical Center, where they were treated and released.   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstormsin much of the Gulf Coast, Florida, the southern and middle AtlanticCoast and the upper Great Lakes; and showers and thunderstorms incentral Oklahoma, the middle and upper Mississippi Valley and thenorthern and central Rockies.   Predicted highs: 60s in eastern Colorado, the northern Rockiesand parts of the Pacific Coast; 90s in Florida, southern Georgia,the Gulf Coast, much of Texas and southern Oregon; 100s in thedesert Southwest and inland valleys of California; and 70s and 80selsewhere.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 34degrees at Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming to 90 at Blythe,Calif.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 67 fair; Boston 67 hazy; Buffalo 65 fair;Charleston, S.C. 73 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 69 foggy; Cleveland 69foggy; Detroit 66 foggy; Miami 78 fair; New York 71 foggy;Philadelphia 73 foggy; Pittsburgh 67 foggy; Portland, Maine 63partly cloudy; Washington 74 foggy.   _Central: Bismarck 53 partly cloudy; Chicago 79 hazy; Dallas-FortWorth 76 partly cloudy; Denver 56 cloudy; Des Moines 63 cloudy;Indianapolis 70 foggy; Kansas City 63 rain; Minneapolis-St. Paul 65cloudy; Nashville 71 foggy; New Orleans 75 cloudy; St. Louis 77 hazy.   _West: Albuquerque 55 windy; Anchorage 57 cloudy; Las Vegas 75fair; Los Angeles 62 cloudy; Phoenix 85 fair; Salt Lake City 61cloudy; San Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 60 fair; Seattle 63 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 68 fair; Toronto 66 foggy.</TEXT></DOC>